-- Asian Stocks Drop as Fed Damps Expectations for Stimulus
-- B y   Y o s h i a k i   N o h a r a   a n d   J a s o n   C l e n f i e l d
-- 2012-04-04T08:45:25Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-04-04/asian-stocks-drop-as-fed-damps-expectations-for-stimulus.html
Asian  stocks  slid, with the benchmark
 index (CRY)  falling the most in more than three months amid market
holidays across the region, as the  Federal Reserve  damped
expectations for more monetary stimulus.  BHP Billiton Ltd. and other resource companies dropped
after crude and prices fell. Japanese shares plunged after the
Nikkei 225 Stock Average dropped below the key level of 10,000.
 Fast Retailing Co. (9983) , Asia’s top clothier, plunged 5.7 percent in
Tokyo after sales at its Uniqlo stores disappointed investors.
SK Telecom Co. slid 3.2 percent in Seoul after Posco sold shares
of the mobile carrier at a discount.  The MSCI Asia Pacific Index fell 1.5 percent to 125.40 as
of 5:38 p.m. in Tokyo, its steepest decline since Dec. 19. The
gauge has risen about 10 percent this year amid signs the  U.S.
economy  is recovering. Gains slowed after  China  last month cut
its target for economic growth as it seeks to cool the property
market and become less dependent on exports.  “The perception is that you’re taking away the safety net
of excess liquidity that lifted asset prices and at the same
time the prospects for growth that beat expectations aren’t that
good,” said  Tim Schroeders , who helps manage $1 billion at
Pengana Capital Ltd. in Melbourne. “Under that scenario and
given the exceptionally good run we’ve had year-to-date, people
are reassessing their risk-reward scenarios.”  Nikkei Below 10,000  The  Nikkei 225 (NKY)  lost 2.3 percent today, falling the most in
five months. The gauge extending losses after the measure dipped
below its 25-day moving average and closed the day under 10,000
for the first time since March 13.  “Today the big question was whether the Nikkei would be
able to hold above 10,000,” said  Kenichi Hirano , general
manager and strategist at Tachibana Securities Co. in Tokyo.
“Once the market fell below that level, investors started to
sell. Negative signals on monetary easing also weighed on
stocks.”  A gauge of volatility on the Nikkei 225 rose 6.9 percent to
20.23, indicating traders expect a swing of 5.8 percent on the
gauge over the next 30 days.  The BSE India Sensitive Index, or Sensex, fell 0.6 percent.
Australia’s S&P/ASX 200 slid 0.1 percent after the nation
unexpectedly posted a second straight monthly trade deficit.
South Korea’s Kospi Index lost 1.5 percent, with a measure of
 volatility  on the gauge’s core stocks adding 1.8 percent.  Fed Signals  Futures on the  Standard & Poor’s 500 Index (SPXL1)  slid 0.4 percent
today. The index fell 0.4 percent in  New York  yesterday after
the Federal Reserve said it’s holding off on increasing monetary
accommodation and U.S. factory orders missed estimates.  Trading volume was below the 30-day average in markets from
Japan to Australia amid public holidays in China,  Hong Kong  and
 Taiwan  and before a U.S. jobs report this week. Payrolls
probably increased in March by more than 200,000 for a fourth
consecutive month as companies became more optimistic about the
outlook for growth, economists predict a report will show on
April 6 in  Washington .  Resource companies fell after the Thomson Reuters/Jefferies
CRB  Index (CRY)  of raw materials fell 0.5 percent yesterday. Oil for
May delivery yesterday declined 1.2 percent to $104.01, the
lowest close since March 30.  BHP slid 1.3 percent to A$34.74.  Rio Tinto Group (RIO) ,
Australia’s second-largest mining company by market value,
declined 0.6 percent to A$66.39.  Fast Retailing Slides  Fast Retailing plunged 5.7 percent to 17,800 yen in Tokyo
after Credit Suisse Group AG said sales at the retailer’s Uniqlo
stores in Japan failed to recover following last year’s March 11
earthquake. The clothier yesterday said domestic same-store
sales at the chain rose 5.1 percent last month from a year
earlier.  Stocks in the Asian benchmark are  valued  at 1.4 times book
value, compared with 2.3 times for the S&P 500 and 1.5 times for
the Stoxx 600, according to data compiled by Bloomberg. A number
below 1 means companies can be bought for less than value of
their assets.  SK Telecom slid 3.2 percent to 138,000 won after Posco,
 South Korea ’s biggest steelmaker, sold 2.3 million of the phone
company’s shares for about 4 percent less than yesterday’s
closing price. Posco, which also sold stakes in KB Financial
Group Inc. and Hana Financial Group Inc. to improve its finances,
declined 1.5 percent to 375,000 won.  Among stocks that gained today, IVRCL Ltd., an Indian
construction company backed by Norway’s central bank, rose 3.6
percent to 71.90 rupees after a group led by billionaire Subhash
Chandra raised its stake in the company. Asian Satellite
Broadcast Pvt., part of Chandra’s Essel Group, bought 5.56
million shares, or 2.08 percent, in IVRCL on April 2 and 3,
according to an exchange filing today.  To contact the reporter on this story:
